This is the main prompt that was used, some captioned with gemini flash, most with gemini pro; sample videos ranged from 6 seconds to 90 seconds:
```
Carefully examine the audio and video provided, then provide a detailed, comprehensive description of all audio, video, and textual information.

Be sure to include highly detailed descriptions of the various visual scenes within the video, noting whether it is day or night, inside or outside, in nature or indoors, detailed description of the speakers' appearance/attire/movements/etc. if one or more speakers are present, etc.

Be sure to include highly detailed descriptions of the various audio elements, including any background noises when applicable, description of voices if any, music that is playing when applicable, etc.  Do not provide a direct transcript, rather provide a detailed summary of what is being discussed.
```
The vector space does not necessarily correlate to the format of the output either - the titles often continue to get high cosine similarity (this is a finetune after all, not a brand new model).  The key conceptual change is including more descriptive information about the audio component, ensuring you describe visual information, and ensuring you have a lengthy (~300 unique tokens gives max length score) description.

# :dreampriest: –––––––––––––––––––––––– :dreampriest: 
# :dreampriest:     SN24 Validation Revamp    :dreampriest: 
# :dreampriest: –––––––––––––––––––––––– :dreampriest: 

Today marks the most significant update to our video validation mechanism since launch. We have a bunch of exciting and important changes to share. Here's the tl;dr:

1. **ImageBind v2**: full finetune of ImageBind with a highly curated gold standard dataset, exemplifying strong video understanding
2. **Token stuffing detection**: classifier for detecting unnatural, token stuffing adversarial caption
3. **Longer captions, more incentive**: incentivizing longer and more unique captions

Let's dig into the details:

# ImageBind v2

## 🎥 Enhanced Training Data:

We generated about 75,000 high-quality video captions using a combination of Gemini Flash and Gemini Pro.
This diverse and rich dataset forms the foundation of the new fine-tuned model. Here's an example caption from the dataset:

```
The video begins with a first-person perspective of a Minecraft world. The player is in a dark cave with a small pool of lava. It sounds like someone is moving around the cave, and there are the sounds of blocks being broken and placed. 

The player places a torch and starts exploring the cave. They talk about how the cave is a giant room, with a lot of stone and dirt. They say that the cave does not have any diamonds. The player then finds a spot with a lot of gold and starts mining it. 

The player comments on the strange green water that they have encountered twice now. They say that the water is in the cave because of an extra biome. 

The player says that they are going to end the video now and that the next video will be a speed build for the train station. They mention that they are going to get a mod that allows them to turn sandstone into sand, which will make their life easier and prevent them from having to find sand.
```
## 📈 Improved Performance:

With this new ImageBind, we are assigning higher cosine similarity scores to richer captions like the one above. As well, we've expanded the context window from 77 tokens in v1 to a much larger 1024 tokens in v2. Example cosign similarity output between v1 and v2:
```
IB v1 cosine similarity:
        title & video: 0.3523820638656616
        caption & video: 0.051597077399492264
IB v2 cosine similarity:
        title & video: 0.3167785406112671
        caption & video: 0.32189327478408813
```
## 🧠 Fine-Tuning Details:

- Full fine-tune, not a LoRA
- Expanded caption context size from 77 tokens to 1024!
- Trained on 75k super HQ video-text pairs
- Over $20k of compute spent on annotating the data and training the checkpoint

## 🔄 Our Iterative Journey to ImageBind v2:

We went through several iterations to nail down the ImageBind v2 model:

1. We trained on high-quality videos and captions, but sampled too many frames. This would have been too compute-intensive for validators, making high-throughput validation challenging.
2. We reduced the frame count, maintaining high embedding quality. However, we realized the default ImageBind text similarity only considered the first 77 tokens, while we aimed for 1000-token captions.
3. We began training a 1024 text token version, offering a great balance between description length and processing speed. The 1024-token version slightly reduces validation throughput, but the trade-off is justified by the significant improvement in description quality.
4. Final Push: We discovered that LoRA (Low-Rank Adaptation) wasn't sufficient for our needs, so we moved to a full fine-tune approach, which is where the magic really got unlocked.

# Updated Scoring Logic 📊

We've made some significant changes to enhance our data quality:
## 🕵️ @jondurbin's Unstuffing BERT model is being used to detect and penalize "stuffed" descriptions. Here's how it works:
- Detects descriptions stuffed with tokens trying to game the scoring system
- Metadata submissions with stuffed descriptions will be discarded
- Descriptions with 75%+ confidence of being stuffed will face penalties
- Check out the model here: https://huggingface.co/jondurbin/unstuffer-v0.2
- This setup will allow us to continuously iterate the model to react to additional stuffing exploits. The training pipeline takes about 3 hours so it's trivial to retrain.
- The MLP tiered description storing model has been replaced with this new Unstuffing BERT model.

## 📏 We've updated our description length scoring.
- Descriptions with very few unique tokens (<=100) get a 35% score reduction
- Descriptions will earn higher and higher rewards up to 300 max tokens. 
- Token counts more than 300 are still appreciated, but do not get further incentivized
- For descriptions between 100-300 tokens, we apply a logarithmic scaling
- This scaling rewards longer, more informative descriptions while preventing excessive length

## 🔢 We've adjusted the balance between query relevance and description relevance back to 70/30

# Impact and Value of These Changes 💎

These updates will significantly improve our dataset quality:

🎯 Better detection of relevant descriptions
🚫 Reduction in "keyword stuffing" and other gaming attempts
📈 Encouragement of more informative, natural descriptions
🔍 Improved balance between query matching and description quality

For SN21, this means:

🧠 Higher quality training data
🎨 More accurate and contextually relevant embeddings to train on for better multi-modality responses
🚀 Potential for improved downstream tasks and applications
